of 40%, some of the people said. The interest =0Arate on offer is roughly S=
OFR plus 4.5%, equating to around 9% at Monday=E2=80=99s rate.=0A=0AI suppo=
se that it is not all that convenient for a SpaceX employee to sell 15% =0A=
of her stock: =E2=80=9CAt SpaceX, staff have regularly had the option of se=
lling shares =0Athrough a tender offer that has, in recent years, occurred =
biannually,=E2=80=9D but =0Amaybe you want to renovate your kitchen between=
 tender offers.=0A=0AStill I feel like there is some continuum between peop=
le who believe =E2=80=9Cyou =0Ashould have roughly 0% of your net worth in =
your employer=E2=80=99s stock, because you =0Ahave large undiversified expo=
sure to your employer in the form of your paycheck =0Aand human capital, so=
 you should do what you can to diversify that exposure =0Awith your investm=
ents,=E2=80=9D and those who believe =E2=80=9Cyou should have roughly 300% =
of =0Ayour net worth in your employer=E2=80=99s stock, because your employe=
r is awesome and =0Ayou should be all in.=E2=80=9D I am, by nature, very mu=
ch a 0% guy.=0A=0AOne gets the sense that everyone at SpaceX is more of a 3=
00% person. Selling =0A15% of your stock would mean owning slightly less Sp=
aceX stock, and one of the =0Amain benefits of working at SpaceX is that yo=
u get to own SpaceX stock.Borrowing=0A15% of the value of your SpaceX stock=
 at SOFR plus 450 means that you get money=0Aandkeep all your SpaceX stock.=
 Obviously it costs you 9%, and you=E2=80=99ll feel bad =0Aabout it if Spac=
eX=E2=80=99s stock goes down, but if you are worried that SpaceX=E2=80=99s =
=0Astock might go down then maybe you shouldn=E2=80=99t work at SpaceX.=0A=
=0A=0ABlue Owl=0A=0AOne important development in the financial industry ove=
r the past 20 years is =0Athat alternative asset managers have become enorm=
ous institutions. It used to =0Abe that a private equity firm was a handful=
 of ex-bankers cobbling together one =0Aleveraged buyout at a time; now Bla=
ckstone Inc. manages a trillion dollars and =0Abarely mentions leveraged bu=
youts. The big firms do private equity, sure, but =0Aalso real estate and i=
nfrastructure and, especially, private credit. Apollo=E2=80=99s =0Aambition=
, now, is not to do leveraged buyouts; it=E2=80=99s to be a one-stop provid=
er of=0Aretirement savings =0A<https://d1io3yog0oux5.cloudfront.net/_86da10=
b3d35d526ba06427591e4dfbf5/apollo/db/2224/21725/pdf/Apollo+2024+Investor+Da=
y+Presentation+.pdf>=0A. These firms have grown, organically and by acquisi=
tion, over many years to =0Abecome gigantic platforms with institutional re=
lationships and scale to do =0Aevery business.=0A=0ABut there are still a l=
ot of small alternative asset managers, who might find =0Ait hard to compet=
e in this age of giant platforms. What can they do=3F Well, if =0Athey arep=
rivate credit managers, the answer is pretty easy: There are tons of =0Atra=
ditional asset managers who are desperate to buy private credit firms, so =
=0Ayou just go and sell yourself toBlackRock =0A<https://www.bloomberg.com/=
